WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.940 --> 00:00:02.860
&gt;&gt;&gt; Ladies and gentlemen, good afternoon.

00:00:02.860 --> 00:00:06.160
Would you please welcome to the stage Chris
Yerga.

00:00:06.160 --> 00:00:10.870
[ Applause ]
&gt;&gt;Chris Yerga: Thank you very much.

00:00:10.870 --> 00:00:13.209
There's actually three of us on stage.

00:00:13.209 --> 00:00:18.650
So I'm joined here with my partners in crime
here, Ellie Powers, who's the lead program

00:00:18.650 --> 00:00:25.550
manager for the Google Play -- we'll get into
that later, and Miles Barr, who runs the engineering

00:00:25.550 --> 00:00:26.550
team.

00:00:26.550 --> 00:00:31.840
So I want to talk to you today about Android
Apps in Google Play.

00:00:31.840 --> 00:00:36.000
So I'm the engineering director for the Google
Play team.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:40.790
And it's my job to make sure that every year,
there's more and more opportunities for you

00:00:40.790 --> 00:00:46.190
as developers to build a successful business
selling your apps in the Play store.

00:00:46.190 --> 00:00:51.589
Now, I want to start by saying thank you.

00:00:51.589 --> 00:00:56.089
Thank you for building incredible apps and
games in the Play Store.

00:00:56.089 --> 00:01:00.579
Thank you for helping the Google Play store
and the Android platform become the fastest

00:01:00.579 --> 00:01:05.080
growing mobile platform around, and thank
you for delighting hundreds of millions of

00:01:05.080 --> 00:01:07.650
users with your products.

00:01:07.650 --> 00:01:12.660
Mobile apps have gotten to this point where
they've become intertwined in our lives in

00:01:12.660 --> 00:01:14.330
a very meaningful way.

00:01:14.330 --> 00:01:21.100
And I had actually, you know, written this
intro the other day, and then just a few hours

00:01:21.100 --> 00:01:24.660
ago, I had an experience that really underlined
it for me.

00:01:24.660 --> 00:01:26.160
I was up on stage.

00:01:26.160 --> 00:01:30.120
I had the privilege to be part of the keynote
this morning.

00:01:30.120 --> 00:01:33.820
And so I talked a bit about Google Play and
all the great stuff that we are launching

00:01:33.820 --> 00:01:34.820
today.

00:01:34.820 --> 00:01:39.810
And then I had a moment when I had to step
offstage when Hugo got to announce the Nexus

00:01:39.810 --> 00:01:40.960
7 tablet.

00:01:40.960 --> 00:01:47.430
So I was sitting on my chair on the side of
the stage and listening to Hugo, and candidly,

00:01:47.430 --> 00:01:51.740
we'd rehearsed that presentation numerous
times before, so the content was a little

00:01:51.740 --> 00:01:52.740
old to me.

00:01:52.740 --> 00:01:56.810
And all of a sudden I discovered, this wasn't
even a conscious thing, I had my phone in

00:01:56.810 --> 00:01:57.990
my hand.

00:01:57.990 --> 00:02:01.280
And what I was doing was I was playing a game
that I had just downloaded.

00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:06.690
So I had recently gone to Japan and got this
insane game, I don't know if anyone is familiar

00:02:06.690 --> 00:02:11.750
with it, called Mushroom Garden, where the
game is, you grow mushrooms, it's exactly

00:02:11.750 --> 00:02:12.750
what it says on the tin.

00:02:12.750 --> 00:02:14.620
There's really nothing more to it.

00:02:14.620 --> 00:02:16.200
But it's really oddly compelling.

00:02:16.200 --> 00:02:19.590
Because you have to check back to see if you're
getting these rare mushrooms.

00:02:19.590 --> 00:02:23.260
I was playing this game and I thought, this
is not a rational thing to be doing.

00:02:23.260 --> 00:02:25.530
Like, I'm in the middle of this keynote presentation.

00:02:25.530 --> 00:02:27.530
There are 6,000 people in the room.

00:02:27.530 --> 00:02:28.650
And I'm playing this game.

00:02:28.650 --> 00:02:34.310
But what it reminded me of is the fact that
I think, you know, the best kind of entertainment

00:02:34.310 --> 00:02:39.810
or the best kinds of products permeate your
life in that way, where they just become a

00:02:39.810 --> 00:02:43.069
part of your behavior, and it's almost like
second thought.

00:02:43.069 --> 00:02:47.440
And these applications, they're not just getting
installed into our devices; they're becoming

00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:49.900
a part of our lives and our daily existence.

00:02:49.900 --> 00:02:58.280
And that, combined with the astounding growth
of Android and the crazy numbers of Android

00:02:58.280 --> 00:03:02.819
activations, presents a huge opportunity for
you as developers.

00:03:02.819 --> 00:03:07.630
So today we're going to talk about what it
takes to grow your business.

00:03:07.630 --> 00:03:12.230
And in order to have a successful business,
there's really, you know, three things that

00:03:12.230 --> 00:03:13.230
you need.

00:03:13.230 --> 00:03:14.490
First is, obviously, you need customers.

00:03:14.490 --> 00:03:18.180
You need people who are coming to your products.

00:03:18.180 --> 00:03:19.180
And then you need revenue.

00:03:19.180 --> 00:03:25.849
You need some means of monetizing those customers
and turning that into revenue for your business.

00:03:25.849 --> 00:03:32.880
And the final thing that you need is data
and insight into how your business is operating

00:03:32.880 --> 00:03:38.340
so that you can optimize your business and
the way that you're conducting things to sort

00:03:38.340 --> 00:03:42.130
of create this virtuous cycle that will then
folds back to the beginning to help you get

00:03:42.130 --> 00:03:44.610
more customers and more revenue.

00:03:44.610 --> 00:03:49.700
We're going to be deep-diving into each one
of these areas a bit today.

00:03:49.700 --> 00:03:54.130
And let's start off talking about customers.

00:03:54.130 --> 00:04:01.459
So in the Google Play team, we really -- we
think about customers on sort of two axes.

00:04:01.459 --> 00:04:06.730
So the first one is that, obviously, we want
to be bringing in an ever-increasing number

00:04:06.730 --> 00:04:10.770
of customers into the front door of the Google
Play store.

00:04:10.770 --> 00:04:16.170
But on the other axis, we also want to be
driving ever-increasing engagement with these

00:04:16.170 --> 00:04:17.170
customers.

00:04:17.170 --> 00:04:18.170
So what do I mean by that?

00:04:18.170 --> 00:04:22.930
So engagement means giving customers more
reasons to come to this store, more reasons

00:04:22.930 --> 00:04:26.880
to keep coming back, giving them a delightful
experience when they use the store and make

00:04:26.880 --> 00:04:33.270
a purchase so that they're happy, they become
regular customers and trusting in the Google

00:04:33.270 --> 00:04:41.010
Play store and are -- we create sort of a
lifelong relationship with them and value.

00:04:41.010 --> 00:04:48.150
And if you think about one of the primary
drivers of bringing an ever-increasing number

00:04:48.150 --> 00:04:53.780
of customers to the store certainly has to
be the astounding rate of Android device activations.

00:04:53.780 --> 00:04:58.960
As we talked about the keynote today, a year
ago, we were at 100 million devices.

00:04:58.960 --> 00:05:02.990
Now we're at 400 million total devices activated.

00:05:02.990 --> 00:05:05.270
I mean, these are just crazy numbers.

00:05:05.270 --> 00:05:09.790
A million devices a day are being activated.

00:05:09.790 --> 00:05:14.690
That's a device for every person in the City
of San Francisco, where we're here today,

00:05:14.690 --> 00:05:15.690
every single day.

00:05:15.690 --> 00:05:17.910
It's just crazy numbers.

00:05:17.910 --> 00:05:23.550
And each one of these users is basically a
potential customer of your apps and games.

00:05:23.550 --> 00:05:29.770
And the other most meaningful thing that we've
done in the last year is the release of the

00:05:29.770 --> 00:05:31.310
Google Play brand.

00:05:31.310 --> 00:05:39.090
So to consumers, Google Play means all of
your digital content, apps, games, music,

00:05:39.090 --> 00:05:46.430
books, movies, and now magazines and TV, available
across your devices and on the Web.

00:05:46.430 --> 00:05:52.320
And so you might, you know, rightly ask yourself,
well, so what does this mean to me as an application

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:53.520
developer?

00:05:53.520 --> 00:05:59.550
Well, by bringing all of these content types
together, we did so in a couple ways.

00:05:59.550 --> 00:06:04.730
The first is, we put everything under a single
brand, but we also brought all these content

00:06:04.730 --> 00:06:07.450
types together in a single store.

00:06:07.450 --> 00:06:11.930
And so the more content types that we launch,
the more reasons people have to come to the

00:06:11.930 --> 00:06:14.479
store, the more reasons they have to come
back.

00:06:14.479 --> 00:06:20.940
And one of the things that we've noticed is
that with each new content type that we launch,

00:06:20.940 --> 00:06:24.790
there's additional people who come to the
store and maybe even make their purchase,

00:06:24.790 --> 00:06:27.680
their first purchase, from one of these content
types.

00:06:27.680 --> 00:06:32.250
So, you know, certainly many people make their
first purchase as an app or game.

00:06:32.250 --> 00:06:37.169
But, you know, when we launched music or launched
books, these people come in, they get over

00:06:37.169 --> 00:06:40.400
that hump of making their first purchase and
every time they come in the front door of

00:06:40.400 --> 00:06:44.830
our store, we're merchandising the full swath
of everything we have, including apps and

00:06:44.830 --> 00:06:49.460
games, to them, you're getting an opportunity
to put your products in front of these users.

00:06:49.460 --> 00:06:57.389
And the more different types of content that
our users are purchasing, the more engaged

00:06:57.389 --> 00:07:00.390
a customer of ours they become.

00:07:00.390 --> 00:07:03.850
And so they have more and more reasons to
frequently come back to the store.

00:07:03.850 --> 00:07:09.729
And we create a deeper relationship with them.

00:07:09.729 --> 00:07:14.889
Now, the other thing that's important about
Google Play is that it's a Google-wide brand.

00:07:14.889 --> 00:07:19.740
So by bringing all this stuff together, we
have the opportunity to bring the full weight

00:07:19.740 --> 00:07:25.509
of Google's resources behind the store in
a couple different areas.

00:07:25.509 --> 00:07:30.090
Promotions, marketing, driving customer awareness,
et cetera.

00:07:30.090 --> 00:07:35.889
One simple but pretty concrete example of
this is the fact that we're now present in

00:07:35.889 --> 00:07:41.460
the universal navigation bar up here that's
at the top of all of Google's Web properties.

00:07:41.460 --> 00:07:48.449
And so this not only gives users sort of a
quick one-click access to the Google Play

00:07:48.449 --> 00:07:54.699
store, but what we've also seen is that for
many users, this is driving the first time

00:07:54.699 --> 00:07:56.900
they've ever visited the Web Store.

00:07:56.900 --> 00:08:02.389
So, you know, we have a lot of people who
use the Device Store on a fairly regular basis.

00:08:02.389 --> 00:08:06.180
But this is driving awareness and giving them
yet another opportunity to come to the store,

00:08:06.180 --> 00:08:10.710
maybe when they're engaged with their desktop
computer or laptop rather than their mobile

00:08:10.710 --> 00:08:11.930
device.

00:08:11.930 --> 00:08:17.319
The other thing that's important here is that
by bringing all this content together into

00:08:17.319 --> 00:08:24.240
sort of a single umbrella brand, it enables
us to much more effectively do marketing and

00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:25.240
promotion.

00:08:25.240 --> 00:08:29.150
So when we launched the Google Play brand,
we did this promotion across all the content

00:08:29.150 --> 00:08:33.050
types, with deeply discounted content, 25-cent
apps.

00:08:33.050 --> 00:08:39.480
It was very successful in not only driving
increased app sales of the things that were

00:08:39.480 --> 00:08:44.510
on sale as well as, actually, things that
weren't part of the promotion, but also driving

00:08:44.510 --> 00:08:48.820
a higher rate of people making their first
purchase from the Google Play store.

00:08:48.820 --> 00:08:54.120
And more recently, we've tried to do some,
you know, more creative things.

00:08:54.120 --> 00:08:59.190
Last week, we did this Play with Collectibles
promotion, where we had a variety of in-game

00:08:59.190 --> 00:09:04.800
items that were available in the Play Store
for a limited time basis across a variety

00:09:04.800 --> 00:09:06.709
of different games.

00:09:06.709 --> 00:09:12.890
And I think this is -- we're starting to see
the first sort of creative different ways

00:09:12.890 --> 00:09:17.110
that we're trying to experiment with marketing
and promotions here.

00:09:17.110 --> 00:09:20.930
You know, I can't really say too much about
our future plans.

00:09:20.930 --> 00:09:26.250
But what I'll tell you is this: Google Play
is hugely important for Google.

00:09:26.250 --> 00:09:27.990
It's a very strategic thing for us.

00:09:27.990 --> 00:09:31.060
We want to -- I mean, we have a great brand.

00:09:31.060 --> 00:09:33.890
We have amazing apps and games that you all
have built.

00:09:33.890 --> 00:09:37.580
I mean, if you think back to, you know, when
I actually joined the team, just under two

00:09:37.580 --> 00:09:42.750
years ago, like, the progress that we've made
in terms of quality of apps and games is just

00:09:42.750 --> 00:09:43.750
astounding.

00:09:43.750 --> 00:09:47.140
So we have something that's really special
and really strategically important to us.

00:09:47.140 --> 00:09:48.820
So we're going to shout it from the rooftops.

00:09:48.820 --> 00:09:52.040
We're going to make a big splash about Google
Play.

00:09:52.040 --> 00:09:53.580
Your grandparents are going to know about
it.

00:09:53.580 --> 00:09:55.621
Your friends on other platforms are going
to know about it.

00:09:55.621 --> 00:09:59.890
And so we're going to continue to do a lot
more in terms of marketing and promotion to

00:09:59.890 --> 00:10:05.230
bring more people into the store.

00:10:05.230 --> 00:10:07.290
So is that working?

00:10:07.290 --> 00:10:10.490
Well, we announced some pretty great numbers
today.

00:10:10.490 --> 00:10:14.030
20 billion total app downloads in the store.

00:10:14.030 --> 00:10:18.740
1.5 billion apps being downloaded per month
out of 600,000 apps.

00:10:18.740 --> 00:10:25.730
So, basically, on any metric that we can measure,
the store is continuing to grow at a very

00:10:25.730 --> 00:10:27.519
fast pace.

00:10:27.519 --> 00:10:34.870
And the users who are driving that growth
are increasingly global in nature.

00:10:34.870 --> 00:10:40.750
So Google Play apps and games are available
in 190 countries and territories.

00:10:40.750 --> 00:10:45.860
132 of those support paid applications.

00:10:45.860 --> 00:10:51.480
We continue to make investments there, trying
to close that gap and offer paid apps in new

00:10:51.480 --> 00:10:53.480
places where we can.

00:10:53.480 --> 00:10:59.480
But in terms of the global footprint of Android
users, we have 92% coverage.

00:10:59.480 --> 00:11:03.420
So 92% of those folks have access to paid
apps.

00:11:03.420 --> 00:11:09.370
And so I think, you know, one of the first
takeaways for you all is just really thinking

00:11:09.370 --> 00:11:14.029
about the global opportunity for Android Apps.

00:11:14.029 --> 00:11:18.170
In the Google Play store, you want to really
make sure that you're thinking about how to

00:11:18.170 --> 00:11:23.470
reach customers in a variety of different
geographies, a variety of different languages,

00:11:23.470 --> 00:11:30.279
to really take advantage of the full market
opportunity here.

00:11:30.279 --> 00:11:37.950
Now, we talked about an amazing number of
device activations.

00:11:37.950 --> 00:11:39.990
But not all devices are alike.

00:11:39.990 --> 00:11:47.840
And with the Nexus 7 tablet, what we aspired
to do was to produce a tablet that -- or an

00:11:47.840 --> 00:11:53.000
Android device maybe in the more generic sense,
that really sets the goalposts for what a

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:56.959
device that contemplates Google Play at its
core could be.

00:11:56.959 --> 00:12:00.820
From the moment you turn on the tablet -- and
I think everyone here is going to be turning

00:12:00.820 --> 00:12:02.779
on a tablet pretty darned soon here; right?

00:12:02.779 --> 00:12:05.570
So that's pretty awesome.

00:12:05.570 --> 00:12:10.640
I had nothing to do with it, but feel free
to applaud.

00:12:10.640 --> 00:12:14.340
The -- as soon as you turn it on, you're immediately,
as soon as you come out of the setup wizard,

00:12:14.340 --> 00:12:19.250
the very first thing you see is your content
library.

00:12:19.250 --> 00:12:24.230
And the other thing that we're doing here
that's pretty novel is, when you activate

00:12:24.230 --> 00:12:32.240
the device and create a Wallet account, you're
given $25 in-store credit for the Google Play

00:12:32.240 --> 00:12:36.730
store so that you can immediately go in and
start buying things from the store.

00:12:36.730 --> 00:12:42.720
And the intention here is to capture people
at that magic moment.

00:12:42.720 --> 00:12:43.720
So you know how it is; right?

00:12:43.720 --> 00:12:44.720
You get a new device.

00:12:44.720 --> 00:12:47.110
You're all amped about it, like, "Oh, this
thing is really cool."

00:12:47.110 --> 00:12:49.730
You want to install the latest game on it
to show off your hardware.

00:12:49.730 --> 00:12:54.030
You want to trick it out with live wallpaper
and widgets and all that stuff.

00:12:54.030 --> 00:12:59.190
So we want to get people right at that magic
moment, give them a direct on ramp to the

00:12:59.190 --> 00:13:03.920
store, give them money to spend to create
those sort of habits so that they become a

00:13:03.920 --> 00:13:06.060
lifelong user.

00:13:06.060 --> 00:13:12.880
I think the other thing that's important here
is that we also preprovision content on this

00:13:12.880 --> 00:13:13.880
device.

00:13:13.880 --> 00:13:18.370
So when you turn on your device and activate
it, you know, you get a movie to watch.

00:13:18.370 --> 00:13:22.440
You get some magazines and a book to read
and things like that, so that you can really

00:13:22.440 --> 00:13:27.880
understand what that experience is like, so
that you're -- you know, you understand the

00:13:27.880 --> 00:13:32.410
value, you're more willing to make a purchase
when you get into the store.

00:13:32.410 --> 00:13:38.940
So a variety of ways that we're bringing customers
to the store and trying to deepen our engagement

00:13:38.940 --> 00:13:43.620
with them to keep them coming back and giving
them more reason to come.

00:13:43.620 --> 00:13:49.130
The next bit of this, obviously, is revenue,
so monetizing these customers.

00:13:49.130 --> 00:13:55.970
And so in terms of revenue, we think of this
in sort of two categories.

00:13:55.970 --> 00:13:59.000
So first is thinking about it from the user
point of view.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:02.250
We want to give users flexible ways to pay.

00:14:02.250 --> 00:14:07.360
And then for you as developers, we want to
give you flexible ways to monetize your applications.

00:14:07.360 --> 00:14:09.660
From the user point of view, a few things
we've done.

00:14:09.660 --> 00:14:14.829
So credit and debit cards clearly continue
to be a very popular way for people to buy

00:14:14.829 --> 00:14:16.610
apps.

00:14:16.610 --> 00:14:21.970
With the new setup wizard that we've done
in Jelly Bean, we've also made it easy for

00:14:21.970 --> 00:14:26.750
users to create a Wallet account and set up
a credit or debit card at that moment when

00:14:26.750 --> 00:14:30.820
you're setting up the device and you're in
that mode of, okay, I've got to configure

00:14:30.820 --> 00:14:32.560
everything and get everything set up.

00:14:32.560 --> 00:14:38.360
So it reduces friction for people purchasing
things in the store afterwards.

00:14:38.360 --> 00:14:42.420
Obviously, credit cards aren't popular everywhere
in the world.

00:14:42.420 --> 00:14:47.890
So in order to address some other markets,
we've also been aggressively working on carrier

00:14:47.890 --> 00:14:50.700
billing as a means to give people a way to
pay.

00:14:50.700 --> 00:14:55.360
And then, as I mentioned, the Google Play
Balance is yet another thing that we're rolling

00:14:55.360 --> 00:14:56.860
out.

00:14:56.860 --> 00:15:02.570
For you as developers, certainly, you know,
a variety of ways to monetize your apps and

00:15:02.570 --> 00:15:07.940
ways that are increasing, you know, ad-funded
and paid apps continue to be very popular

00:15:07.940 --> 00:15:11.529
and viable ways to monetize your apps.

00:15:11.529 --> 00:15:14.529
In-app billing, been a huge success for us.

00:15:14.529 --> 00:15:17.490
We'll be talking about that in some greater
detail.

00:15:17.490 --> 00:15:21.880
But subscriptions is kind of like -- the way
I think of subscriptions is sort of like the

00:15:21.880 --> 00:15:24.350
next wave of in-app billing.

00:15:24.350 --> 00:15:30.399
It's an opportunity to create a recurring
revenue relationship with your customers.

00:15:30.399 --> 00:15:32.740
Business models.

00:15:32.740 --> 00:15:36.160
So you're going to hear this, I'm going to
say this time and time again.

00:15:36.160 --> 00:15:37.910
We're going to talk about international.

00:15:37.910 --> 00:15:41.680
International markets really is where a lot
of the growth is happening, and international

00:15:41.680 --> 00:15:43.880
markets are key to revenue growth.

00:15:43.880 --> 00:15:48.560
So fully two-thirds of Google Play revenue
is coming from outside the U.S.

00:15:48.560 --> 00:15:56.990
And, now, the United States remains the largest
single country where Android devices are being

00:15:56.990 --> 00:15:58.930
activated on a daily basis.

00:15:58.930 --> 00:16:03.870
However, in aggregate, there's more devices
being activated outside the U.S. on a daily

00:16:03.870 --> 00:16:05.589
basis than inside.

00:16:05.589 --> 00:16:07.329
And you can look here.

00:16:07.329 --> 00:16:11.160
We've listed some of the top markets for paid
apps.

00:16:11.160 --> 00:16:16.410
And even when you just limit this to the top
five, you're already spanning the Americas,

00:16:16.410 --> 00:16:18.579
Europe, and Asia.

00:16:18.579 --> 00:16:24.760
So really want to be thinking about international
for monetizing your apps.

00:16:24.760 --> 00:16:32.310
And I want to start off here and talk a little
bit about an international success story.

00:16:32.310 --> 00:16:39.010
So between April of 2011 and April of this
year, revenue in Japan and Korea increased

00:16:39.010 --> 00:16:42.589
14X. 14 times.

00:16:42.589 --> 00:16:44.570
That's crazy growth.

00:16:44.570 --> 00:16:48.570
Now, what happened during that period of time
that accounts for this?

00:16:48.570 --> 00:16:54.480
Well, certainly, we activated quite a lot
of Android devices in those regions during

00:16:54.480 --> 00:16:55.480
that time.

00:16:55.480 --> 00:16:57.080
So that's responsible for some of it.

00:16:57.080 --> 00:17:01.320
And certainly there was a lot of, you know,
really compelling apps that were built and

00:17:01.320 --> 00:17:02.320
released.

00:17:02.320 --> 00:17:10.439
But what really made this happen is this almost
magic combination of direct carrier billing

00:17:10.439 --> 00:17:11.439
and in-app billing.

00:17:11.439 --> 00:17:14.829
So we're going to talk a little bit about
how that works.

00:17:14.829 --> 00:17:22.509
So in Japan and Korea, you know, credit cards
aren't necessarily, you know, the predominant

00:17:22.509 --> 00:17:24.169
way that people are used to buying things.

00:17:24.169 --> 00:17:30.229
And, you know, actually, I should go further
than that and say that people actually expect

00:17:30.229 --> 00:17:33.580
to be able to purchase things using their
phone in these regions.

00:17:33.580 --> 00:17:41.000
And so we've really aggressively gone after
carrier billing deployments to enable that.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:45.940
And we've gotten to a point now where I'm
very happy to say that in Korea and Japan,

00:17:45.940 --> 00:17:52.629
full 90% of users are on a mobile network
that offers carrier billing with Google Play.

00:17:52.629 --> 00:17:57.120
Now, this isn't, you know, a phenomenon that's
limited to Asia.

00:17:57.120 --> 00:18:01.769
Actually, everywhere that we've deployed carrier
billing, Europe and the United States, et

00:18:01.769 --> 00:18:03.850
cetera, it's been wildly popular.

00:18:03.850 --> 00:18:06.350
It's just such a frictionless way to purchase
things.

00:18:06.350 --> 00:18:11.090
It's actually the way that I actually purchase
content myself.

00:18:11.090 --> 00:18:16.519
So worldwide, globally, fully 73% of Google
Play app purchases are made with carrier billing

00:18:16.519 --> 00:18:17.549
when it's available.

00:18:17.549 --> 00:18:23.140
So if it's available to users, they predominantly
choose that as a form of payment.

00:18:23.140 --> 00:18:28.629
We've made some pretty significant investments
in carrier billing this year, launched with

00:18:28.629 --> 00:18:32.049
a number of new carriers across a number of
countries.

00:18:32.049 --> 00:18:35.289
And you can see the list of countries it's
available here.

00:18:35.289 --> 00:18:38.679
We're going to continue to really aggressively
push this.

00:18:38.679 --> 00:18:44.409
Google Play is the largest Appstore that supports
direct carrier billing.

00:18:44.409 --> 00:18:49.770
And we see it as one of the huge growth prospects
for bringing more revenue to the store.

00:18:49.770 --> 00:18:53.320
So carrier billing launching in Japan and
Korea.

00:18:53.320 --> 00:18:58.879
As part of that success story, every time
we would deploy a new carrier in those regions,

00:18:58.879 --> 00:19:04.860
we would see giant jumps in revenue, so there
was this built-up, pent-up demand there that

00:19:04.860 --> 00:19:07.129
we were unlocking with each of these launches.

00:19:07.129 --> 00:19:13.149
But then the other thing that turned out to
be super popular in these regions was freemium

00:19:13.149 --> 00:19:17.009
business model games that leveraged in-app
purchases.

00:19:17.009 --> 00:19:26.289
So in-app purchasing has been a huge breakout
success for Google Play, both for developers,

00:19:26.289 --> 00:19:28.259
and users have really embraced it as well.

00:19:28.259 --> 00:19:33.739
The thing that I really like about in-app
purchasing is, it's one of these things where

00:19:33.739 --> 00:19:37.620
it's kind of like a fundamental enabling piece
of infrastructure; right?

00:19:37.620 --> 00:19:40.940
So we give you guys this relatively simple
API.

00:19:40.940 --> 00:19:45.220
What it allows you to do is to, you know,
make direct charges from within your apps

00:19:45.220 --> 00:19:46.450
to users.

00:19:46.450 --> 00:19:51.580
But you've taken that and used it in some
incredibly creative ways to figure out a wide

00:19:51.580 --> 00:19:54.399
variety of different ways to monetize your
apps.

00:19:54.399 --> 00:20:01.109
So, you know, there's the tried and true things,
like, you know, in-app currency or, you know,

00:20:01.109 --> 00:20:07.220
collectibles or items in games, or maybe unlocking,
you know, premium features in an application,

00:20:07.220 --> 00:20:08.220
et cetera.

00:20:08.220 --> 00:20:14.700
But we've also seen some other really creative
things, like people do time-limited offers.

00:20:14.700 --> 00:20:21.669
I think one developer did this thing where
you download the free game and, like, within

00:20:21.669 --> 00:20:26.440
the first 15 or 30 minutes, like, long enough
that the user understands what the game play

00:20:26.440 --> 00:20:30.479
is and probably has a pretty good sense of
what the value of the game is, they offer

00:20:30.479 --> 00:20:31.479
them a discount.

00:20:31.479 --> 00:20:34.620
Like, you can unlock the game this one time
for a discounted rate.

00:20:34.620 --> 00:20:40.009
We've seen a lot of various creative applications
of in-app purchasing.

00:20:40.009 --> 00:20:44.960
One specific case study here is from TinyCo.

00:20:44.960 --> 00:20:47.849
They implemented our in-app billing API.

00:20:47.849 --> 00:20:55.470
And they also did something else that's really
important here, which is timely and kind of

00:20:55.470 --> 00:20:56.619
frequent content updates; right?

00:20:56.619 --> 00:21:02.259
So you're not only selling things to your
users, but by keeping the content fresh, you

00:21:02.259 --> 00:21:06.049
give your users more reason to keep coming
back to your game and more things to purchase,

00:21:06.049 --> 00:21:09.789
once again, sort of deepening your engagement
with those users.

00:21:09.789 --> 00:21:14.080
They implemented virtual currency in their
app via in-app billing.

00:21:14.080 --> 00:21:18.499
And in their own words here from Suli Ali,
the CEO, they said, "Google Play has the highest

00:21:18.499 --> 00:21:21.809
average revenue per paying user of all app
stores.

00:21:21.809 --> 00:21:26.909
This and other Android metrics make us" -- once
again, their words -- "Android zealots," which

00:21:26.909 --> 00:21:29.289
we obviously love to hear.

00:21:29.289 --> 00:21:30.350
So that's in-app billing.

00:21:30.350 --> 00:21:31.490
That kind of brings us to today.

00:21:31.490 --> 00:21:38.019
And so, as I say, the next wave of this is
subscriptions.

00:21:38.019 --> 00:21:45.169
So the point I want to get across to you here
is to think broadly about what subscriptions

00:21:45.169 --> 00:21:46.400
can mean for you.

00:21:46.400 --> 00:21:51.330
It would be kind of easy to fall into a trap
and say, well, subscriptions, that's for,

00:21:51.330 --> 00:21:56.210
like, maybe a newspaper or a comic book app
or something where there's some periodic timed

00:21:56.210 --> 00:21:58.869
content that's coming through.

00:21:58.869 --> 00:22:05.059
But you should really think broadly about
what recurring value you can deliver to users

00:22:05.059 --> 00:22:08.859
that they would be willing to pay and engage
in a subscription with you for.

00:22:08.859 --> 00:22:13.429
If you think about it this way: Every in-app
conversion you do, right, that's this opportunity

00:22:13.429 --> 00:22:17.840
you get where the user has said, okay, I'm
really enjoying this experience.

00:22:17.840 --> 00:22:19.690
There's some value here I'm willing to pay
for.

00:22:19.690 --> 00:22:25.970
If you could convert that instant into a recurring
revenue opportunity with that user, you're

00:22:25.970 --> 00:22:31.039
more deeply engaged with that user, you have,
you know, not only a relationship with them,

00:22:31.039 --> 00:22:34.679
but an ongoing revenue stream, that's a very
powerful thing.

00:22:34.679 --> 00:22:40.200
So as an example of maybe some, you know,
broad ways to think about subscriptions, one

00:22:40.200 --> 00:22:42.869
of our launch partners is Glu.

00:22:42.869 --> 00:22:46.519
And they've used subscriptions in an interesting
way.

00:22:46.519 --> 00:22:52.640
They implement this thing you can see up here
that's, like, these VIP gold and silver packages.

00:22:52.640 --> 00:22:58.899
What that does is it -- it gives you Glu credits
that you can spends in the game and some other

00:22:58.899 --> 00:23:00.320
premium features.

00:23:00.320 --> 00:23:05.380
But the interesting thing is that it does
that across a portfolio of their games.

00:23:05.380 --> 00:23:11.159
So no matter what game you purchase the subscription
for, you get the benefits of that subscription

00:23:11.159 --> 00:23:13.859
across a suite of their different games.

00:23:13.859 --> 00:23:18.570
And so the cool thing about that is, now you're
kind of building this relationship with a

00:23:18.570 --> 00:23:21.859
user where they're kind of invested in your
games; right?

00:23:21.859 --> 00:23:27.100
And so maybe they're going to try other games
or other applications that you have where

00:23:27.100 --> 00:23:30.529
they might not have otherwise done so.

00:23:30.529 --> 00:23:34.989
The CEO of Glu has this to say, that their
subscriptions-based VIP club continues to

00:23:34.989 --> 00:23:39.179
grow in popularity as gamers take advantage
of significant bonus value and the easy sign-up

00:23:39.179 --> 00:23:41.649
process offered on Google Play.

00:23:41.649 --> 00:23:47.859
So think hard about how you can make subscriptions
work for you in creative ways as well.

