applications have gotten fairly high, right?

00:46:21.460 --> 00:46:27.269
I mean, as everybody is sort of raising their
game in terms of user experience and app development.

00:46:27.269 --> 00:46:31.569
And so I think there's a couple things that
are worthy to mention here.

00:46:31.569 --> 00:46:34.750
The first is really making benefit of user
reviews.

00:46:34.750 --> 00:46:40.930
You want to aim to have a great app with great
design, great usability that users are going

00:46:40.930 --> 00:46:43.030
to rate highly for a couple reasons.

00:46:43.030 --> 00:46:48.630
One is high ratings in the Google Play store
is every racer who rates your app highly is

00:46:48.630 --> 00:46:53.240
promoting your application to others who come
through the store and it's an opportunity

00:46:53.240 --> 00:46:55.450
for you to close those conversions.

00:46:55.450 --> 00:47:01.200
Also reviews are a great way to get feedback
about issues you might be having in your applications.

00:47:01.200 --> 00:47:05.250
I wanted to talk a little bit about what we
mean when we say focus on the user from a

00:47:05.250 --> 00:47:08.269
case study here from this app called Pocket.

00:47:08.269 --> 00:47:14.990
Pocket's a cool app that lets you basically
clip content from the web or videos or blogs

00:47:14.990 --> 00:47:20.430
or things like that and all bring them together
in a single, unified reading experience.

00:47:20.430 --> 00:47:28.160
And what Pocket did is they've built their
application from the ground up on Android.

00:47:28.160 --> 00:47:36.380
So they make use of the Android framework
owes share intent so that you can add share

00:47:36.380 --> 00:47:41.329
intent to the Pocket application from all
of other Android apps, they also use a cloud-to-device

00:47:41.329 --> 00:47:48.050
messaging and you can clip from the web and
send a notification to the Pocket web running

00:47:48.050 --> 00:47:54.190
on the Android device, basically everything
to have that sort of unique Android experience.

00:47:54.190 --> 00:47:58.660
And I think when they first started off and
this is probably true for a number of developers

00:47:58.660 --> 00:48:03.519
early on it wasn't really apparent like what
the best practices for Android apps should

00:48:03.519 --> 00:48:05.279
look like.

00:48:05.279 --> 00:48:14.180
Now with the release of our Android UX guidelines
and design guidelines, we make that much easier.

00:48:14.180 --> 00:48:19.849
So I'd encourage you to take a look at the
UX and design guidelines and there's a few

00:48:19.849 --> 00:48:23.170
other things you could consider doing here.

00:48:23.170 --> 00:48:25.450
Do beta tests.

00:48:25.450 --> 00:48:30.000
Reach out to users, maybe have a usability
study of your application.

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:36.009
Think hard about all the things you can do
to deliver a compelling experience to your

00:48:36.009 --> 00:48:37.910
users.

00:48:37.910 --> 00:48:44.119
so the next thing, obviously, we've been talking
a lot about is localization.

00:48:44.119 --> 00:48:50.319
Think about what are the different regions
that I want to take my app to and think about

00:48:50.319 --> 00:48:56.289
the global marketplace that's available there
and how you can reach it.

00:48:56.289 --> 00:49:02.769
Maybe you start with just localizing your
Google Play store listing or maybe eventually

00:49:02.769 --> 00:49:08.220
engage with a professional translation firm
or take advantage of the auto translation

00:49:08.220 --> 00:49:10.589
feature that we heard about.

00:49:10.589 --> 00:49:16.039
Now, localization is -- takes many forms.

00:49:16.039 --> 00:49:19.150
One case study we want to talk about here
is Foursquare.

00:49:19.150 --> 00:49:25.160
So Foursquare, as you know, it's a local app
where people can check in at various venues,

00:49:25.160 --> 00:49:31.609
et cetera, and one thing that they noticed
is that they started to have growth outside

00:49:31.609 --> 00:49:35.079
of the U.S. in an interesting way.

00:49:35.079 --> 00:49:42.519
They had users that were actually helping
to build out their location database for them

00:49:42.519 --> 00:49:48.230
predominantly started with native English-speakers
who were abroad, but by building out their

00:49:48.230 --> 00:49:53.970
location database for them, these users were
really helping them grow and provide a compelling

00:49:53.970 --> 00:49:56.700
experience to users outside of the U.S.

00:49:56.700 --> 00:50:04.250
So they invent advised that by giving batchers
to these super users to encourage this behavior.

00:50:04.250 --> 00:50:10.900
They did anales to the places where the greatest
amount of activity was happening and then

00:50:10.900 --> 00:50:15.740
they then localized their application into
a dozen languages to target those different

00:50:15.740 --> 00:50:17.040
markets.

00:50:17.040 --> 00:50:22.450
And the result of that is now fully 50% of
their user base is now outside of the U.S.

00:50:22.450 --> 00:50:28.789
So that's a way for you to think about ways
to sort of get your app available into different

00:50:28.789 --> 00:50:29.789
markets.

00:50:29.789 --> 00:50:36.270
the third thing to tab here is making your
app look great on tablets, a lot of Android

00:50:36.270 --> 00:50:40.349
tablets are going to be sold this year particularly
around the holiday season and we think that

00:50:40.349 --> 00:50:43.090
we've just released a killer one with the
Nexus 7.

00:50:43.090 --> 00:50:49.240
So, you know, tablet users don't just want
an exploded-up version of a phone application

00:50:49.240 --> 00:50:56.839
so think about how you can make your applications
tablet-optimized and deliver a really compelling

00:50:56.839 --> 00:50:59.079
experience on tablets.

00:50:59.079 --> 00:51:05.019
A case study I want to get in here is from
mint.com who I think really did an excellent

00:51:05.019 --> 00:51:06.499
job of this.

00:51:06.499 --> 00:51:13.390
So what Mint does -- they use the Android
fragments APIs fairly -- fairly extensively,

00:51:13.390 --> 00:51:19.960
they have an application that adapts itself
dynamically to phones and tablets, they've

00:51:19.960 --> 00:51:24.570
done, actually both seven-inch and 10-inch
optimized versions of their application on

00:51:24.570 --> 00:51:25.570
tablets.

00:51:25.570 --> 00:51:31.099
And using the fragments API it actually -- adapting
their 10-inch tablet layout to support seven-inch

00:51:31.099 --> 00:51:36.530
tablets, something they got done in under
a week.

00:51:36.530 --> 00:51:44.240
The other thing they noticed, however, is
that the usage patterns of their applications

00:51:44.240 --> 00:51:46.810
varied significantly between phones and tablets.

00:51:46.810 --> 00:51:53.549
So what Mint saw is that on phones they would
see kind of peak usage around midday, maybe

00:51:53.549 --> 00:51:57.980
around lunchtime or something like that but
the duration of those sessions were fairly

00:51:57.980 --> 00:51:59.380
short.

00:51:59.380 --> 00:52:02.690
People would make just go in and check their
bills or check their balances or something

00:52:02.690 --> 00:52:08.829
like that but tablet users would peak much
later in the day, in the evening time or after

00:52:08.829 --> 00:52:13.490
dinner, and those sessions lasted much longer
and those users were much more engaged with

00:52:13.490 --> 00:52:15.530
their devices.

00:52:15.530 --> 00:52:20.410
And so the way Mint put that information to
use for them is in their tablet versions of

00:52:20.410 --> 00:52:25.010
their applications they actually added new
features there that aren't present on the

00:52:25.010 --> 00:52:30.999
phone to enable users to engage with their
budget and do more things in the mode where

00:52:30.999 --> 00:52:34.170
they're kind of willing to more deeply engage
there.

00:52:34.170 --> 00:52:39.750
So the other thing that you could do here
is actually Mint added tablet screen shots

00:52:39.750 --> 00:52:43.720
to the play store to promote the fact that
they have this sort of premium experience

00:52:43.720 --> 00:52:44.759
on tablets.

00:52:44.759 --> 00:52:49.059
So think hard about how to reach tablet users
and the things that you can do to deliver

00:52:49.059 --> 00:52:54.670
and experience to them that really leverages,
you know, the capabilities of their device

00:52:54.670 --> 00:53:02.089
rather than giving them just a translated
phone experience.

00:53:02.089 --> 00:53:04.280
number four here is revenue model.

00:53:04.280 --> 00:53:09.940
You know, think creatively and figure out
what's the best revenue model for my application.

00:53:09.940 --> 00:53:14.170
As we've talked about a couple times here,
there's a variety of different models here.

00:53:14.170 --> 00:53:20.140
You know, if you look at the sort of top grossing
charts in the Google Play store, a lot of

00:53:20.140 --> 00:53:26.109
those apps are Freemium apps, right, free
apps that sell in-app purchases, but not all

00:53:26.109 --> 00:53:27.109
of them are.

00:53:27.109 --> 00:53:31.980
So, you know, there's no sort of one-size-fits-all
model for success.

00:53:31.980 --> 00:53:37.480
So maybe if you haven't considered this in
a while, it's time to think if there's a different

00:53:37.480 --> 00:53:39.549
way to monetize your apps.

00:53:39.549 --> 00:53:47.180
An example here is from the folks at Cellfish
C-E-L-L-fish, see what they did there?

00:53:47.180 --> 00:53:52.559
And they sell these live wallpapers and they
license things from movies and sports teams

00:53:52.559 --> 00:53:54.109
and things like that.

00:53:54.109 --> 00:53:59.720
And when they started out, they had a paid
app version of their live wallpaper that they

00:53:59.720 --> 00:54:05.660
sold, but they decided to try a different
tack and so what they did is they offered

00:54:05.660 --> 00:54:14.750
a free version of their app that only offered
some sort of generic NFL branding and then,

00:54:14.750 --> 00:54:19.769
from within the application they enabled people
to purchase, you know, custom versions for

00:54:19.769 --> 00:54:23.140
their favorite sports teams and things like
that.

00:54:23.140 --> 00:54:26.509
They also went a step further and they offered
packages.

00:54:26.509 --> 00:54:31.499
So you could maybe get the live wallpaper
as well as a ring tone or theme or something

00:54:31.499 --> 00:54:32.680
else as a bundle.

00:54:32.680 --> 00:54:37.529
It's like, well, just another dollar more
for the upsell and you get this package deal

00:54:37.529 --> 00:54:39.989
and they've had great success with this model.

00:54:39.989 --> 00:54:44.019
The other thing that they did which is something
that we've mentioned earlier as well is keeping

00:54:44.019 --> 00:54:45.920
their content fresh.

00:54:45.920 --> 00:54:51.539
So they've done like seasonal customizations,
you know, around the holiday times and things

00:54:51.539 --> 00:54:52.539
like that.

00:54:52.539 --> 00:54:58.050
And when the Giants won the Super Bowl, they
actually had confetti flying in the live wallpaper

00:54:58.050 --> 00:55:04.730
just a few minutes after the end of the game
So, you know, think about how inapp or something

00:55:04.730 --> 00:55:10.579
like subscriptions work for your application
and figure out if there's some creative ways

00:55:10.579 --> 00:55:15.089
you could reconsider your business models
if you haven't really given that a look in

00:55:15.089 --> 00:55:19.910
a while
so the final thing we want to talk about today

00:55:19.910 --> 00:55:26.210
in terms of our tips is investing in analytics
and marketing.

00:55:26.210 --> 00:55:31.319
We talked a lot about, you know, Google analytics
and the insight it gives you and once you've

00:55:31.319 --> 00:55:37.891
made the investment to build a really compelling
application experience, you know, you want

00:55:37.891 --> 00:55:39.630
to like tell the world about it.

00:55:39.630 --> 00:55:43.480
You want to invest in marketing and promotion
to get it out there.

00:55:43.480 --> 00:55:49.619
And you can think creatively there's a variety
of different ways to do that.

00:55:49.619 --> 00:55:58.650
So I want to talk here about a case study
with Smule, so their marketing is not terribly

00:55:58.650 --> 00:55:59.650
traditional.

00:55:59.650 --> 00:56:05.869
They make these really cool apps like Magic
Piano and Songify that use your phone in creative

00:56:05.869 --> 00:56:07.509
ways that are musical in nature.

00:56:07.509 --> 00:56:13.180
So because their apps are so musical, video
is a really effective way for them to get

00:56:13.180 --> 00:56:14.740
their point across.

00:56:14.740 --> 00:56:22.700
And so it turns out that, you know, they get
a lot of engagement from video ads as well

00:56:22.700 --> 00:56:24.349
as YouTube channels.

00:56:24.349 --> 00:56:31.319
They partnered with some of these YouTube
superstars to focus on use either their products

00:56:31.319 --> 00:56:36.630
in their videos or do videos about using their
products and they found some interesting thing,

00:56:36.630 --> 00:56:45.980
when they combined that marketing and promotion
with analytics, what they saw was that users

00:56:45.980 --> 00:56:51.950
who inquired the app through this Jimmy Wong
video on YouTube, once they actually had the

00:56:51.950 --> 00:56:58.510
app were twice as engaged with the app and
used it a lot more than a other users.

00:56:58.510 --> 00:57:04.099
And when they took a look at this, they found
that the reason was that in the video, it

00:57:04.099 --> 00:57:08.239
was actually very good at explaining how to
use the application and so they got a whole

00:57:08.239 --> 00:57:13.369
'nother level of insight there on not only
how am I doing a conversion, how am I getting

00:57:13.369 --> 00:57:20.140
a customer to acquire my application, but
how am I also using these channels to get

00:57:20.140 --> 00:57:24.489
customers who are more engaged with my app
and actually have a better understanding of

00:57:24.489 --> 00:57:30.740
the value that they're getting as well.

00:57:30.740 --> 00:57:35.990
In summary, focus on the user, localize your
apps, make it look great on tablets, find

00:57:35.990 --> 00:57:40.819
your revenue model, use any of the variety
of ways to monetize your app and make sure

00:57:40.819 --> 00:57:43.970
that you invest in analytics and marketing.

